Title: SPeed and Runway INdependent Technologies (SPRINT) X-Plane Demonstration Project                                                             -       47.524         62.113
Description: The SPeed and Runway INdependent Technologies (SPRINT) X-Plane Demonstration Project is developing
and demonstrating the fundamental technologies needed for combined high speed and vertical take-off and landing (VTOL)
capabilities in a single aircraft. This program culminates in the fabrication and flight test of a demonstrator that validates the critical
technologies in a representative environment and reduces technical, schedule, and cost risk for a follow-on operational system.
High speed VTOL aircraft are highly desired in a variety of military missions such as contested logistics under attack, infiltration/
exfiltration, electronic warfare, personnel recovery, troop transport and armed escort. The SPRINT Demonstrator is envisioned to
transition to a Services component for further risk reduction flight testing.

Prior to FY 2026, this program was funded in PE 0603286E, Project AIR-01.

FY 2026 Plans:
- Complete critical design activities.
- Finalize subsystem development (propulsion system, thermal management system, hydraulics, electrical system, etc.), vehicle
integration, and engineering drawing release.
- Continue toward final aircraft software and aircraft flight control algorithm development.
- Continue flight test planning and airworthiness certification.
- Integrate with the flight test facility for connectivity, data transfer, and flight safety requirements.
- Execute demonstrator vehicle manufacturing and assembly, to include material acquisition and unique tooling for fabrication.
- Initiate ground station and human-machine interface development.
- Initiate ground system checkouts.
FY 2027 Plans:
- Finalize flight test planning and airworthiness certification.
- Complete structural proof load test to verify the built aircraft matches structural design predictions.
- Complete final software integration lab verification testing to ensure the system operates as intended including the proper
vehicle responses in the presence of simulated failures.
- Complete subcomponent manufacturing and assembly.

