Title: Artificial Intelligence (AI) Reinforcements (AIR)                                                                                         -       51.610         32.174
Description: AI Reinforcements (AIR) is developing and demonstrating dominant tactical autonomy for multi-ship, beyond visual
range (BVR), real-world air combat missions. This program is focused on developing highly accurate models that are orders of
magnitude faster than the present state-of-the-art and then using those models to unlock novel and robust AI-driven autonomy
approaches. An operations-centric development approach will be enabled through the use of human-on-the-loop F-16 aircraft. On
piloted platforms, AIR's algorithms will automate tactical control tasks transforming junior pilots from low-level tacticians into high-
level mission commanders. For unpiloted platforms, AIR will enable vehicles to perform missions with minimal human oversight.
The outcome of this program will be an AI air combat capability that works in dynamic, operationally representative environments.
The transition partner is the U.S. Air Force.

Prior to FY 2026, this program was funded in PE 0603286E, Project AIR-01.

FY 2026 Plans:
- Initiate incorporation of F-16 aircraft into the AIR integration and testing pipeline and iterate development through testing.
- Scale the AI-driven autonomy to four-ship operations with increased complexity.
- Improve speed and predictivity of model development.
- Incorporate dissimilar capabilities, non-stationaries, and deceptive environments to the multi-agent AI training.
- Quantify the robustness of AI agent performance by rigorously evaluating its response to realistic operational uncertainties,
such as sensor degradation and communication loss, and validate its effectiveness in critical mission scenarios like Offensive and
Defensive Counter Air (OCA/DCA).
FY 2027 Plans:
- Expand operational testing into increasingly complex and contested environments, including electronic warfare scenarios, to
rigorously evaluate system robustness and adaptability.
- Advance multi-platform collaboration by integrating heterogeneous teams, such as manned-unmanned formations, to assess
the scalability of the autonomous teaming capabilities.
- Maintain compatibility with other related combat autonomy efforts, enabling rapid integration and testing of new capabilities
within the operational framework.
FY 2026 to FY 2027 Increase/Decrease Statement:




