Title: Lunar Assay via Small Satellite Orbiter (LASSO)                                                                                   -              -        8.900
Description: The Lunar Assay via Small Satellite Orbiter (LASSO) program will optimize autonomous navigation and propulsion
in support of advancing Space Situational Awareness capabilities in cislunar space. The program will build a low-cost satellite,
launched as a secondary payload, to demonstrate these capabilities in Very Low Lunar Orbit (VLLO), which is the most
challenging environment in cislunar space due to continually destabilizing orbits, lack of navigation aids (i.e., GPS), variable
gravity and operation in close proximity to terrain. While operating in VLLO, LASSO will collect high-resolution data regarding
accessible water ice on the moon by capturing data about resource distribution and quantities to support future in-situ resource
utilization (ISRU) investigation. Such discoveries support future lunar exploration. With improved navigation, propulsion, and
autonomous control, the LASSO satellite will achieve VLLO and remain there for long duration while building a statistically
significant understanding of lunar resources. Additional research related to this effort is funded within PE 0602023E, Project
ACS-01.

Prior to FY 2027, this program was funded in PE 0602702E, Project TT-07 and PE 0602023E, Project ACS-01.

FY 2027 Plans:
- Conduct final mission design planning and verification testing of spacecraft subsystems.
- Verify spacecraft and integrated sensor performance through full fidelity Software-in-the-Loop (SWIL) simulations.
FY 2026 to FY 2027 Increase/Decrease Statement:
The FY 2027 increase reflects the shift from applied research activities in PE 0602023E, Project ACS-01 to advanced technology
development in this PE/Project.
Title: Rubble to Rockets (R2)                                                                                                            -              -        7.533
Description: The Rubble to Rockets (R2) program will create a flexible, robust, and agile platform for the production and
characterization of raw material for use in rocket body fabrication in a rapidly deployable format. The program will take in
indigenous materials, convert it to usable feedstock, characterize the material properties, then adaptively update a sounding
rocket's structural design with predictive changes in system level performance. Leveraging material informatics and innovative
processing and manufacturing techniques within an agile, rapid iteration schedule structure, R2 will dramatically drive down
the timeframes and scale needed for production from months to days. R2 will overcome current limitations in processing mixed
and blended scrap by developing tooling and processing approaches that can accommodate widely variable inputs, use online
analysis of the upcycling process along with rapid testing to update and develop material informatics models to predict minimum
material properties of blended or contaminated scrap streams, and update the design to account for the new materials while

