Title: Scaled Hypersonics Studies and Concepts                                                                                              -              -       56.000
Description: Studies conducted under this program will examine and evaluate emerging technologies that seek to disrupt the
current paradigms for the development approach for supersonic cruise-missile capabilities by using rapid manufacturing to
iteratively build and test new enhanced technologies. This initiative will focus on those technologies which will enable scalable,
fast, and agile production of hypersonic components at significantly reduced costs.

FY 2027 Plans:
- Enhanced Propulsion Efficiency: Analyze new propulsion technologies, such as Rotating Detonation Engines (RDE) among
others, that offer the potential for increased fuel efficiency in flight, leading to longer range and reduced operating costs.
- Improved Thrust-to-Weight Ratio: Design a higher thrust-to-weight ratio that could enable more agile and responsive aircraft.
- Advanced Flight Capabilities: Analyze unique characteristics of new technologies, e.g. RDEs, that could unlock new flight
capabilities and operational scenarios.
- Higher Thermodynamic Efficiency: Design new propellant methods for increased pressure that allows for more work to be
extracted from the combustion process.
- Compact Engine Design: Analyze new design spaces for increased efficiency to allow for a more compact engine design for a
given power output.
- Scalable Production: Develop processes and production lines for high throughputs of hypersonic components.
FY 2026 to FY 2027 Increase/Decrease Statement:
The FY 2027 increase reflects studies and concepts initiations including, but not limited to, the advancement of new technologies
to enable scalable, fast, and agile production of hypersonic components at significantly reduced costs through enhanced



