Title: DARPA Lift Challenge                                                                                                                  -       13.360              -
Description: The DARPA Lift Challenge addresses limitations in existing unmanned aircraft system (UAS) technologies, aiming
to incentivize innovative designs that achieve a 4:1 payload-to-weight ratio. This approach tackles airframe cost, payload capacity,
operational cost, and overall efficiency through a combination of objective and subjective prize categories. The challenge
spans 12 months, encompassing design, build, competition logistics, and post-challenge tracking. Success will be measured
by milestones such as registration rates, Federal Aviation Administration (FAA) certifications, consistent team engagement,
and the quality of submitted designs. Ultimately, the challenge seeks to identify and test revolutionary UAS designs, with robust
participation from over 100 teams and multiple competitors demonstrating the target 4:1 payload-to-weight capability.

FY 2026 Plans:
- Initiate challenge logistic set up following public announcement.
- Conduct challenge event including set up, competition, award announcement, and tear down.
FY 2026 to FY 2027 Increase/Decrease Statement:
The FY 2027 decrease reflects program completion.
Title: Control of Revolutionary Aircraft with Novel Effectors (CRANE)                                                                        -        6.287              -
Description: The Control of Revolutionary Aircraft with Novel Effectors (CRANE) program is developing and demonstrating
revolutionary improvements in aircraft controls technology. The program will design, build, and flight test an aircraft able
to fly and maneuver at altitude relying on state-of-the-art Active Flow Control (AFC) technology. AFC is a broad term that
encompasses a range of technology approaches; it includes a number of control mechanisms which alter the aerodynamic
flow field through ejection or suction of fluid via an orifice on a lifting body. An emphasis of the program is on assessing AFC
component technologies, risk reduction and experimentation, integrated testing, fabrication and demonstration of a relevant scale
novel and innovative aircraft. Technologies, design tools and models developed and demonstrated under this program will be
made available to all Services as well as the civilian aerospace sector for application to future air systems development.

Prior to FY 2026, this program was funded in PE 0603286E, Project AIR-01.


